<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
    PaneFlow release entitlements (US-023).

    Consumed by scripts/sign-macos.sh (codesign entitlements flag) when
    signing Developer-ID-distributed .app bundles for tagged releases (`v*`).

    Why each key is here:

    com.apple.security.app-sandbox = false
        PaneFlow spawns user shells and arbitrary child processes (the whole
        point of a terminal). The sandbox would either block these execs or
        confine them to a private container, breaking parity with every other
        terminal emulator. Distribution-signed (Developer ID) apps run
        unsandboxed by default, so this key is technically a no-op — kept
        explicit per US-023 AC1 so reviewers can see the decision was deliberate.

    com.apple.security.automation.apple-events = true
        Lets the terminal (and shells started inside it) drive other apps via
        osascript / NSAppleEventDescriptor — common in dev workflows
        (`osascript -e 'tell app "Finder" to ...'`, `open -a`, etc.).

    com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit = true
        GPUI compiles Metal pipeline state objects on first use; wgpu's
        Metal backend likewise creates MTLComputePipelineStates from
        runtime-generated MSL. Both fall under the hardened-runtime JIT
        rule even though there is no LLVM-style codegen.

    com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory = true
        Required alongside allow-jit for some libdispatch / ARC paths under
        hardened runtime. Apple recommends enabling both together for any
        app that calls into Metal or WebKit-derived shader compilers.

    com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation
        REMOVED 2026-05-07 to match Zed's release entitlements
        (zed/crates/zed/resources/zed.entitlements, where the key is
        commented out). It was originally reserved for the planned
        MCP host (paneflow-workstream EP-004), which would dlopen()
        user-installed transport plugins from third-party Team IDs at
        PaneFlow's own process level. EP-004 has not shipped and the
        entitlement was suspected of contributing to the v0.2.12
        macOS "boxes drawn, no glyphs" bug — under hardened runtime,
        disable-library-validation changes the trust chain for dylibs
        loaded out of /System/Library/PrivateFrameworks/, which is
        where libFontParser and libCoreText live. Re-add this key
        when EP-004 ships.

    com.apple.security.cs.allow-dyld-environment-variables = true
        Allows PaneFlow's own process to honour DYLD_LIBRARY_PATH /
        DYLD_FRAMEWORK_PATH for plugins it loads via dlopen (see the
        disable-library-validation note above). Hardened runtime
        strips DYLD_* by default; enabling this entitlement is the
        canonical way to opt back in. Like disable-library-validation,
        this affects only the PaneFlow process — child shells set
        DYLD_* on their own subprocess environments independently.

    NOTE: com.apple.security.get-task-allow is INTENTIONALLY ABSENT here.
    A distribution build with get-task-allow=true is rejected by
    notarytool (`The executable requests the com.apple.security.
    get-task-allow entitlement`). Use packaging/macos/paneflow.dev.entitlements
    for local debug signing where lldb attach is needed.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>com.apple.security.app-sandbox</key>
    <false/>
    <key>com.apple.security.automation.apple-events</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-dyld-environment-variables</key>
    <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
